@article{osaki_meridional_1972,
	abstract = {The hydrodynamics of meridional circulation in the radiative zone of a rotating star has been studied. The Eddington-Sweet formulation of the circulation velocity, in which the convective transport of energy by the flow is assumed to compensate for the excess or deficiency of the radiation flux, is confirmed for a "slowly" rotating star. On the other hand, apparent singularities of the circulation velocity in the case = a and near the stellar surface are found to be due to improper uses of the Eddington-Sweet formulation. When the convective transport of energy is inefficient, the energy equation reduces to the thermal conduction equation, in which the excess or deficiency of the radiation flux results in local heating or cooling, and the star manages ot redistribute angular velocity of rotation in such a way that there is no meridional circulation. The Goldreich-Schubert instability destroys the above-mentioned steady rotation, but it is argued that a new steady state is likely to be established in which a balance exists between the meridional circulation and the irregular motion due to this instability. Key words: Eddington-Sweet formulation; Goldreich-Schubert instability; Meridional circulation; Steady rotation.},
